title: For Sale:  Colt Match Target™ M4 Carbine
postcontent:
I have a Colt Match Target™ M4 Carbine complete lower with 2 stage trigger and 6-position collapsible stock for sale. I've seen recent completed auctions for these go for around $700 so I was asking $700 but I lowered it to $600. 

As far as I know, this build was never completed and there are new parts. But there are some parts that are obviously used so I have to classify this sell as a used gun. I will only sell to an Indiana resident and it would be nice to see a LTCH but not required. I like to verify I'm selling to a legitimate person but I don't document anything unless you want me to. If you want a bill of sale, I can do that. I'm flexible.

When checking the original configurations of the Colt Match Target™ M4 Carbines, I found they were originally produced to be 49 state legal and had a blind pinned stock. Basically, the stock looked like it was collapsible but wasn't. I also didn't find any with 2 stage triggers in original configuration. Two changes that would've probably been done to an original to make it a good match grade shooter lower has already been completed. They were also shipped out with 10 round magazines to make their 49 state legal market. I don't have anything but 30 round mags I can throw in for the right deal.

If you want a good head start on a nice Colt build, this lower is perfect. The only things I would change on the lower is the standard grip, trigger guard and stock. I'd probably go with an Ergo or something more comfortable for me and a SOPMOD style stock. That's just personal preference for me, but for you, this is a good starting platform with a name brand Colt lower.

I am negotiable and have ammo, mags, and other accessories we can work out a deal for the interested party. Let me know if you're interested and we can try to make something happen.

title: For Sale:  Elk antlers - 6X6
postcontent:
Bought this set a few years ago from a gun shop going out of business. He had them on his wall for decoration, but I don't know where he got them. It is a matched 6X6 set of elk antlers. Show pleasing age, but obviously didn't sit in the elements all that long, as they aren't weathered - just some scattered age cracks from hanging indoors. A couple of the tine tips are broomed/chipped off (showed one), but the aging on it shows it was done long ago - possibly even when the animal was alive. I have used them for photo props and had intended to hang them in a man cave someday, but we are doing some reorganizing and I really don't have the room to store them indefinitely. They measure 42" from base to the farthest tine - that is measuring straight, not following the curve of the antlers and not measuring from the brow tines. They are well matched and very nice.

So, time for them to have a new home. Put them in your man cave. Cut them up for grips. Cut them up for chew toys (there is a big market for that, especially on ebay, and I could get a lot more for them selling them that way than what I am asking if you come pick them up and haul them off). $150 firm picked up in Hickory, NC. This is well below market value for them. Not really interested in trades, but you could pass something by me if you like.

Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Oak deer rattler calls for use or resale
postcontent:
A friend of mine used to manage a vocational training shop who would contract manufacturing out to interested parties. A local man designed these oak deer rattlers and had them make up a pallet of them. He died before paying and they sat on a pallet gathering dust. My friend wanted to clear some space, so I bought 10 of them to try and sell before buying the whole pallet, never got around to it, then he found another job and I don't know what happened to the rest. At any rate, the man who designed them had an instructional video of him using the rattler that he showed my friend and it worked very well - he called a lot of deer in with them and hunted with them himself. You rattle with it, beat and paw the ground with it, etc. Of course, the video was with the man and I never got a copy.

So, as I clean things out, I found my box of these. They are new in the box. They come in a plain white box and are very well made. The handle is about 13.5" long, to give you an idea of scale. Production cost on them was $10 or $12 each and the man sold them for $25 or $30 (he started making them himself, then went full production when they caught on around here). I'd like to sell the whole lot of 10 for $35, picked up in Hickory, NC. Price is firm. Not terribly interested in trades, but you can try me. Maybe we can find something I need and you don't.

Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Read before  Purchase
postcontent:
Armslist ads are being posted requiring a permit to purchase for face to face sales of rifles and shotguns.  Federal law does not require a permit to purchase these firearms within the state.  If you feel you are covering yourself by requiring a permit, go ahead, that is your right though not your responsibility.   Please understand that this is not Federal law and quite likely not your state law either. 
Laws differ between sales from individuals and sales from FFL holders. 
You must also consider the type of firearm being sold.
Shipping firearms has its own set rules as well. 

For more information please visit the ATF website http://www.atf.gov/content/firearms-frequently-asked-questions-unlicensed-persons#gca-unlicensed-transfer
The NRA has provided information regarding state laws as well as federal. You may also want to renew your membership while you are at http://www.nraila.org/gun-laws/state-laws/iowa.aspx
